# Ideas for data storytelling

## You

What do you care about?
Nuclear weapons/energy

What do you know about?
The physics and history behind nuclear weapons.

What decisions do you face?
Which datasets to use/trust (much of the data on nuclear weapons is misleading/propaganda or classified)


## Seven templates

Training Kit (https://learn.lambdaschool.com/ds/module/recedjanlbpqxic2r) explains the seven templates from Priceonomics.

Can you apply the templates to your topics? 

1. Geographic Variation
Strength of nuclear weapons detonations by country.

2. Trend related to the news
Nuclear accidents by severity (recent nuclear disaster in Russia)

3. Who does that?
Number of weapons in each nuclear power.

4. Answering a question people care about
Timeline of the Doomsday Clock

5. Valuable to businesses
Profit/Cost ratio for synthesis of nuclear isotopes.

6. What's the most popular?
Number of countries with nuclear weapons and their yields.

7. Cost/Money rankings
Cost of maintaining nuclear regulation agencies

## Misconceptions

What misconceptions do people have about your topic?
How easy it is to detonate a nuclear weapon.
That bigger weapons are more dangerous.

## Examples

What data storytelling example inspires you?


Could you do a new hypothesis, for the same question?


Could you do a new question, for the same topic?


Could you do a new topic, with the same "style"?


## Data

Where could you search for data about your topic?
Nuclear regulation agencies (Nuclear Regulatory Comission.
Civilian boards (Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, World Nuclear Association)

